Why are brains split in half
Bilateral symmetry came first
The brain didn't split in half. The body did — and the brain followed. Bilateral symmetry in animals evolved somewhere around 550-600 million years ago, probably in early bilaterian worms. The selective pressure was locomotion. If you're moving through an environment in a consistent direction, it helps to have a front and a back, a left and a right. Radial symmetry works fine for organisms that sit in one place and let the world come to them — jellyfish, sea anemones. But once you're navigating, bilateral symmetry gives you streamlined movement, balanced mechanical forces, and paired sensory organs that can triangulate.
The nervous system, including what eventually became the brain, developed within this bilaterally symmetric body plan. It's two halves because everything is two halves. Two eyes, two ears, two arms, two kidneys. The brain's bilateral structure is, at its most basic level, a consequence of the body plan it's embedded in.
Contralateral wiring
Each hemisphere primarily controls and receives input from the opposite side of the body. This contralateral organization is ancient and somewhat mysterious — there's no completely settled explanation for why the wiring crosses rather than staying ipsilateral. One leading hypothesis is that it relates to the optic chiasm: in early vertebrates, the visual system crossed so that each hemisphere could coordinate a complete sensorimotor loop — see something on the left, respond with the right side of the body — in a way that minimized processing delays. Once the crossed wiring was established for vision and motor control, everything else followed, and it became locked in by evolutionary constraint.
But then something interesting happened with specialization
Having two of everything creates a redundancy problem. Two hemispheres processing identical information in identical ways is metabolically expensive and computationally wasteful. So evolutionary pressure favored lateralization — having each hemisphere develop relative specializations rather than being perfect mirrors.
This is the key insight: bilateral structure created the opportunity for lateralization, and metabolic efficiency created the pressure for it. Running a brain is extraordinarily expensive — roughly 20% of your metabolic budget for 2% of your body mass. Any architectural trick that lets you do more with less gets selected for aggressively.
Lateralization effectively doubles your computational diversity without doubling your hardware. Instead of two hemispheres doing the same thing and checking each other's work, you get two hemispheres doing complementary things and integrating their outputs. One narrows attention, the other broadens it. One categorizes, the other contextualizes. You get two modes of cognition for the price of one brain.
The predator-prey pressure
There's compelling evidence from comparative biology that lateralization is heavily driven by the simultaneous need to do two fundamentally different things at once: forage and avoid being eaten. Birds show this beautifully. Many species use their left eye (right hemisphere) to scan for predators — broad, vigilant, contextual awareness — while using their right eye (left hemisphere) for focused tasks like pecking at specific seeds. Fish, amphibians, and even insects show analogous patterns.
This maps directly onto the attentional modes we discussed in the lateralization conversation. The broad, vigilant, contextual mode and the narrow, focused, manipulative mode aren't just cognitive preferences — they're survival necessities that need to operate simultaneously. Having two hemispheres with different attentional biases lets an organism do both at once, which a single unified processor couldn't.
The social dimension
In highly social species, lateralization intensifies. This makes sense because social environments are precisely where you need both modes running simultaneously at their highest capacity. You need focused attention on the specific individual you're interacting with — reading their signals, planning your response — while simultaneously maintaining broad awareness of the group dynamics, potential threats, and social context. Primates, corvids, and other socially complex species tend to show more pronounced lateralization than their less social relatives.
Why not more than two?
This is the interesting flip question. If two complementary processing modes are better than one, why not three or four? Partly because the body plan constrains it — bilateral symmetry gives you two, and evolving a third hemisphere would require a radical developmental reorganization. But there may be a deeper reason. Two modes may represent something close to an optimal decomposition of the fundamental cognitive problem: you need one system that simplifies and controls, and one system that remains open and receptive. These are arguably the two irreducible poles of how any agent can relate to its environment. Adding a third mode might not buy you a genuinely new kind of processing — it might just be a variation on one of the two existing poles.
Connecting it back
This evolutionary story reinforces why building lateralization into artificial systems is both important and hard. The split isn't an accident of biology — it's a deeply optimized solution to a fundamental problem of cognition: that understanding the world requires simultaneously narrowing and broadening, simultaneously grasping and remaining open, simultaneously committing to an interpretation and maintaining sensitivity to everything the interpretation leaves out. Current LLMs do one pole of this extraordinarily well. The architecture of the transformer is essentially a perfection of the left hemisphere's strategy — narrow, sequential, categorical, confident. What's missing is its evolutionary complement.